10. Difference between Gallery, Form and Data Table?

âœ… GALLERY:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ I use Galleries to display multiple records in a scrollable list or card-style layout, especially when working with data from SharePoint lists or Collections. 
ğŸ‘‰ It's very flexible â€” I can fully customize each gallery item by adding buttons, images, icons, based on the appâ€™s needs 
ğŸ‘‰ I also leverage (Gallery.Selected) to pass data between screens, such as opening a detail form or edit form(screen) depend on the userâ€™s selection.

âœ… FORMS:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ I use Forms when I need users to view, create, or edit single record at a time easily.
ğŸ‘‰ It automatically bind the fields to the data source, its saves a lot of time when building input screens.
ğŸ”¹ There are mainly three types of Forms I work with:
ğŸ‘‰ Display Form â€“ for read-only data viewing, 
ğŸ‘‰ Edit Form    â€“ for editing existing records,
ğŸ‘‰ New Form     â€“ for creating new records.

âœ… DATA TABLE:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ I use Data Tables when I need to display multiple records in a tabular format (similar to Excel), but compared to gallery, data tables have less customization.
ğŸ‘‰ Itâ€™s a good when users mainly need to view data quickly.

Example:
ğŸ‘‰ In one app, I used a Gallery to show a list of products, a Form to edit product details, and a Data Table to show a quick, read-only summary of orders.
